---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const blogContent = `
<p>We didn't design Perqed's solver stack. We got stuck, and then we got unstuck, and
when we looked back at what we'd reached for, there was an architecture.</p>

<h2>The Run That Wouldn't Converge</h2>

<p>We were trying to prove R(4,6) ≥ 36 — a known Ramsey lower bound from 1989.
The certificate is a 2-coloring of the edges of K<sub>35</sub> with no red K<sub>4</sub>
and no blue K<sub>6</sub>. Simulated Annealing (SA) is the standard move for this kind of
search: define an energy function that counts violations, anneal until energy hits zero,
hand the adjacency matrix to Lean for verification.</p>

<p>Except SA didn't converge. Eight workers. Five hundred million iterations. The best
energy across all workers: <strong>E = 12</strong>. Not zero. Not trending toward zero.
Just sitting there across multiple seeds and reheat schedules — a glass floor.</p>

<p>This is where a human mathematician's instinct kicks in: something structural is wrong.
SA doesn't hit consistent floors by accident.</p>

<h2>The Symmetry Reduction</h2>

<p>The first move was to restrict the search space. Every known R(4,6) witness in the
literature is a <em>circulant graph</em>: a graph on N vertices where the adjacency
relation depends only on the circular distance between vertices. On N=35, the full
graph coloring search space is 2<sup>595</sup>. Restricting to circulant colorings
reduces it to 2<sup>17</sup> — 131,072 states. That's not a search problem, that's a
<em>table</em>.</p>

<p>We implemented circulant SA — a mutation operator that flips an entire distance class
at once instead of individual edges. The energy floor moved slightly but held. Something
was fundamentally wrong with the circulant space itself, not just our annealing schedule.</p>

<h2>The Right Question</h2>

<p>At this point, the obvious thing is to tune hyperparameters. More workers. Different
cooling schedules. Reheats. But 2<sup>17</sup> states is enumerable — a modern
computer can touch every point in that space in milliseconds. The real question wasn't
<em>how to search better</em>, it was <em>whether a solution exists at all</em>.</p>

<p>This is where we reached for an SMT solver.</p>

<p>SMT (Satisfiability Modulo Theories) solvers like Z3 work differently from heuristic
search. They don't explore the space — they reason about it. The core engine is
CDCL (Conflict-Driven Clause Learning): when the solver hits a contradiction, it doesn't
just backtrack, it synthesizes a new clause that captures <em>why</em> that branch failed
and adds it permanently to its knowledge base. The solver learns the geometry of the
problem in real-time. For a 2<sup>17</sup>-state boolean space, this is almost unfairly fast.</p>

<p>We encoded the problem as 17 boolean variables — one per circulant distance class. The
clique constraints became SAT clauses. We fed it to Z3 and waited.</p>

<p>Z3 came back in seconds: <strong>UNSAT</strong>.</p>

<h2>What UNSAT Actually Means</h2>

<p>This is the result that changed the project's direction. UNSAT doesn't mean "we couldn't
find a solution." It means <em>no solution exists</em>. Z3 proved — not found, not estimated,
<strong>proved</strong> — that there is no circulant 2-coloring of K<sub>35</sub> that witnesses
R(4,6).</p>

<p>The glass floor wasn't a search failure. SA was correctly reporting that the circulant
space has no valid coloring. We were looking in the wrong place.</p>

<p>That's a mathematical lemma. A standalone result, independently interesting, machine-verifiable.
And until we built the ResearchJournal, Perqed was just going to discard it.</p>

<h2>The Statefulness Problem</h2>

<p>Human mathematicians don't throw away dead ends. Their notebooks are full of lemmas that
didn't lead to the main result but are still true. A failed proof attempt isn't wasted
work — it's negative evidence that constrains future attempts.</p>

<p>Perqed was stateless. Every run started from scratch. The ARCHITECT had no memory of what
had been proven in previous runs. It would plausibly try circulant SA again on the next
attempt, not knowing Z3 had already closed that door permanently.</p>

<p>We built the ResearchJournal to fix this: a typed, persistent store of lemmas,
observations, and dead ends. Critically, it includes a distillation step before
anything enters the ARCHITECT's context — only structured, claim-sized entries get
injected, never raw logs. The ARCHITECT now begins each attempt knowing what has already
been established:</p>

<pre><code>### PREVIOUSLY ESTABLISHED LEMMAS & OBSERVATIONS ###
- [LEMMA] No circulant 2-coloring of K_35 witnesses R(4,6)
  (Evidence: Z3 UNSAT: 17-var encoding, circulant 2^17 space exhausted)
- [OBSERVATION] SA on K_35 R(4,6) converged at E_min=12 (attempt 1)
  (Evidence: 500,000,000 iters × 8 workers)</code></pre>

<h2>The Stack We Ended Up With</h2>

<p>None of this was planned. It emerged from following what was broken:</p>

<table>
<thead>
<tr><th>Layer</th><th>Tool</th><th>Role</th><th>How we got here</th></tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>Formulation</td><td>LLM (Gemini)</td><td>Translate problem → search config</td><td>Always planned</td></tr>
<tr><td>Exploration</td><td>Simulated Annealing</td><td>Heuristic witness search over 2<sup>595</sup> graphs</td><td>Standard tool for Ramsey search</td></tr>
<tr><td>Exact verification</td><td>Z3 (SMT)</td><td>Prove or disprove constrained sub-spaces</td><td>SA hit a glass floor we couldn't escape</td></tr>
<tr><td>Certification</td><td>Lean 4</td><td>Formally verify every claimed result</td><td>Always planned</td></tr>
<tr><td>Memory</td><td>ResearchJournal</td><td>Accumulate proven intermediate results</td><td>Z3 returned UNSAT and we almost threw it away</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p>The insight isn't that these tools are good — it's that they're good for <em>different
subproblems</em>. SA is excellent at rapid, unconstrained exploration over enormous spaces.
Z3 is exact and complete over small, constrained ones. Lean rejects anything either tool
gets wrong. And the LLM navigates between them, deciding which subproblem to attack next.</p>

<p>What we didn't anticipate was that the solver outputs themselves — including the UNSAT
proofs — are results worth keeping. The ResearchJournal turns a pipeline of attempts
into a cumulative record of mathematical knowledge. That's the step from search engine
to theorem prover.</p>

<h2>What's Next</h2>

<p>We still don't have the R(4,6) witness. The Z3 UNSAT result tells us it isn't circulant —
which rules out the simplest class of candidates and rules in an entire research direction:
the witness, if it exists at 35 vertices, has a structure we don't yet understand.</p>

<p>The architecture's job is now to figure out what kind of structure that is. The ARCHITECT
knows the circulant space is closed. The next pivot might be partial symmetry, or a MaxSAT
solver to prove the exact minimum energy achievable in the unconstrained space, or something
neither of us has thought of yet.</p>

<p>That's the point. We're not guiding the search anymore — we're building an engine that learns
what to search.</p>

<hr>

<p><em>Perqed is open source. <a href="https://github.com/bneb/perqed">Follow us on GitHub</a>
or <a href="/minutiae/">watch the agent think in real time</a>.</em></p>
`;
---

